explanation:
osal_id_t: need the typedef to know the underlying type pointed-to by outid and obj_id (is it an integer type, a pointer, or a struct) so one can decide whether a pointer to it could/should be const.

OS_object_token_t: need the full struct definition (fields and any const qualifiers) to see whether token is logically input-only in this function (only read) or if any fields are expected to be modified here; this determines if the token parameter could be a pointer-to-const.

OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish (prototype): this call receives token and &final_id. Its parameter const-qualification and whether it modifies the token or the id determine whether token or the id pointer could be const in OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew. The prototype (and ideally implementation) is required to know if token is mutated/locked/unlocked or if the id argument is written.

OS_NotifyEvent (prototype): need its parameter types/const-qualification to check whether passing token->obj_id (by value) or any pointers here would impose non-const requirements on token or its fields.

OS_SUCCESS and OS_OBJECT_ID_UNDEFINED (macros/definitions): need their definitions and types to ensure final_id type and usages are compatible with const qualification decisions (for example if these expand to address expressions or const objects).
